g the Channel and with both countries increasing their involvement in maritime affairs, English and French naval expansion was intertwined. Directly and indirectly, the two kingdoms influenced their neighbours' sea programmes. The book first examines the administrative transformations of both navies, then goes on to discuss fiscal and technological change, and finally assesses the material expansion of the respective fleets. In so doing it demonstrates the close relationship between naval power and state strength in early modern Europe. One important argument challenges the received wisdom about the relative weakness of French naval power when compared with that of England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEarly Modern History. 4aMaritime History. 7aHISTORY / Military / Naval.2bisacsh  aCardinal de Richelieu.  aChatham.  aCouncil of Marine Causes.  aDeptford.  aFrench Wars of Religion.  aKing Charles I.  aKing Francis I.  aKing Henri II.  aKing Henry VIII.  aKing Louis XIII.  aLa Couronne.  aLa Rochelle.  aLe Havre.  aMarseilles.  aMary Rose.  aQueen Elizabeth I.  aShip Money.  aSovereign of the Seas.  aSpanish Armada.  aThe English Channel.  aTransnationalism.  aWarships.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800103993?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800103993423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800103993/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles